// Auto-migrated from the original static guide HTML. Structural markup
// and code samples are preserved; inline styles, scripts, and the guide's
// own bespoke syntax-highlight token classes were stripped so every guide
// renders through the one shared GuideReader stylesheet.
export const html: string = "<section id=\"section\">\n<div>\n<span>INDEX OF SHEETS</span>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"#foundations\"><span>01</span> Foundations &amp; Philosophy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#project-vs-app\"><span>02</span> Projects vs. Apps</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#settings\"><span>03</span> settings.py</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#urls\"><span>04</span> urls.py \u2014 Routing</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#views\"><span>05</span> views.py \u2014 Logic</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#models\"><span>06</span> models.py \u2014 Data</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#migrations\"><span>07</span> Migrations</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#admin\"><span>08</span> admin.py</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#forms\"><span>09</span> forms.py</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#templates\"><span>10</span> Templates</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#tests\"><span>11</span> tests.py</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#wsgi-asgi\"><span>12</span> wsgi.py / asgi.py</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#odds\"><span>13</span> Manage.py &amp; the Rest</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#flow\"><span>14</span> The Full Request Flow</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#tips\"><span>15</span> Pro Tips &amp; Gotchas</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#uiux\"><span>16</span> UI/UX Practices Used Here</a></li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"foundations\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 01 / FOUNDATIONS</span>\n<h2>What is Django, actually?</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Before touching a single file, you need the mental model. Skipping this is why vanilla developers feel like Django is \"magic\" \u2014 it isn't magic, it's just a very opinionated set of decisions made for you, in advance, by people who built dozens of sites and got tired of repeating themselves.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>DEFINITION</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>In vanilla development, every request you handle is a blank page. You read the URL string yourself, parse query parameters yourself, open a database connection yourself, write SQL by hand, escape HTML yourself to avoid XSS, and stitch together a string of HTML to send back. You own <em>everything</em>, which means you also own every mistake.</p>\n<p><strong>Django is a web framework</strong>: a pre-built skeleton of code that already solved those problems, and instead asks you to fill in the parts that are unique to <em>your</em> application \u2014 your data shapes, your business rules, your page content. It follows a philosophy called <strong>\"Don't Repeat Yourself\" (DRY)</strong> and ships as \"batteries-included\": a database layer (ORM), a templating engine, a forms system, an admin panel, a security layer, and a routing system all arrive in the box, pre-wired to cooperate.</p>\n<p>Think of vanilla development as building a house by forging your own nails. Django is a house built from a kit of pre-cut, pre-measured lumber \u2014 you still decide the layout, the rooms, the paint, but you are no longer responsible for whether a nail holds weight.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>MVC vs. MVT \u2014 the naming that confuses everyone</h3>\n<p>You've likely heard of <strong>MVC (Model\u2013View\u2013Controller)</strong> from other frameworks. Django uses a variant called <strong>MVT (Model\u2013View\u2013Template)</strong>, and the naming maps strangely if you compare it word-for-word. Here is the direct translation:</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Classic MVC term</th><th>Django's term</th><th>What it actually is</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Model</td><td><code>models.py</code></td><td>Same concept. The data and its rules.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Controller</td><td><code>views.py</code></td><td>Confusing! In Django, the <strong>view is the controller</strong> \u2014 it contains logic, not visuals.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>View (the visual part)</td><td><code>templates/*.html</code></td><td>What MVC calls the \"View\" (the HTML), Django calls the <strong>Template</strong>.</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>NAMING TRAP</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>The single most common confusion for newcomers: in Django, a <strong>\"view\" is not the HTML page</strong>. A view is a Python function or class \u2014 pure logic. It decides <em>what data</em> to fetch and <em>which template</em> to hand it to. The actual visual markup lives in the <strong>template</strong>. Keep repeating this until it's automatic: <em>View = brain. Template = face.</em></p></div>\n</div>\n<h3>The philosophy: convention over configuration</h3>\n<p>Vanilla code has zero conventions \u2014 you can structure a project however you like, and that freedom is exactly why two vanilla codebases written by two different people look nothing alike. Django enforces conventions: every app has a <code>models.py</code>, every app can have a <code>views.py</code>, migrations live in a <code>migrations/</code> folder, settings live in one predictable place. This is a trade: <strong>you give up some freedom, and in exchange you gain the ability to open any Django project on Earth and roughly know where things live.</strong> This is the same philosophy behind why a Toyota engine bay is laid out predictably across models \u2014 a mechanic anywhere can service it without re-learning the car from zero.</p>\n<div class=\"pillquote\">\"Explicit is better than implicit, but predictable is better than both \u2014 Django chooses predictable, then makes the predictable parts explicit.\"</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"project-vs-app\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 02 / STRUCTURE</span>\n<h2>Project vs. App \u2014 the distinction nobody explains well</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">This single distinction trips up almost every newcomer, because in vanilla code there's only ever \"the project\" \u2014 one folder, one codebase. Django splits that into two different ideas on purpose.</p>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">THE PROJECT</span>\n<p>A project is the <strong>whole website</strong> \u2014 the container. It holds global settings, the root URL table, and the WSGI/ASGI entry points. You create exactly one project per website. Created with:</p>\n<pre><code><span>django-admin</span> startproject mysite</code></pre>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">THE APP</span>\n<p>An app is a <strong>self-contained feature module</strong> \u2014 blog, accounts, payments, inventory. A project can (and usually does) contain <em>many</em> apps. An app can even be reused across different projects. Created with:</p>\n<pre><code><span>python</span> manage.py startapp blog</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Mental Model</h4><span>ANALOGY</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Think of the <strong>project</strong> as a shopping mall, and each <strong>app</strong> as one store inside it. The mall provides shared infrastructure: electricity (settings), the directory board at the entrance (root URLs), security (middleware). Each store (app) is independently stocked and managed \u2014 a \"blog\" app doesn't need to know anything about the \"payments\" app to function \u2014 but they all plug into the same mall wiring.</p>\n<p>This is why a mature Django project's folder structure looks like a project folder wrapping several little app folders, each with its own <code>models.py</code>, <code>views.py</code>, <code>urls.py</code>, and <code>templates/</code>.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Anatomy of a freshly generated project</h3>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>File Tree</h4><span>mysite/</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<pre><code>mysite/ <span># the root folder \u2014 not a Python package itself</span>\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 manage.py <span># command-line utility \u2014 your remote control</span>\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 mysite/ <span># the actual project package (same name, confusing but standard)</span>\n\u2502 \u251c\u2500\u2500 __init__.py <span># marks this folder as a Python package</span>\n\u2502 \u251c\u2500\u2500 settings.py <span># global configuration \u2014 sheet 03</span>\n\u2502 \u251c\u2500\u2500 urls.py <span># root URL table \u2014 sheet 04</span>\n\u2502 \u251c\u2500\u2500 asgi.py <span># async server entry point \u2014 sheet 12</span>\n\u2502 \u2514\u2500\u2500 wsgi.py <span># sync server entry point \u2014 sheet 12</span>\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 blog/ <span># an app, created separately</span>\n \u251c\u2500\u2500 __init__.py\n \u251c\u2500\u2500 admin.py <span># sheet 08</span>\n \u251c\u2500\u2500 apps.py <span># app-level config</span>\n \u251c\u2500\u2500 models.py <span># sheet 06</span>\n \u251c\u2500\u2500 views.py <span># sheet 05</span>\n \u251c\u2500\u2500 tests.py <span># sheet 11</span>\n \u251c\u2500\u2500 migrations/ <span># sheet 07 \u2014 auto-generated DB history</span>\n \u2502 \u2514\u2500\u2500 __init__.py\n \u2514\u2500\u2500 urls.py <span># app-level routes (you add this yourself)</span>\n</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>RULE OF THUMB</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>If you can describe a piece of functionality in one short noun phrase \u2014 \"blog\", \"checkout\", \"user profiles\" \u2014 it's probably one app. If you find yourself needing the word \"and\" to describe an app's job (\"blog <em>and</em> comments <em>and</em> newsletter\"), it's probably two or three apps pretending to be one.</p></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"settings\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 03 / CONFIGURATION</span>\n<h2>settings.py \u2014 the project's nervous system</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">In vanilla code, configuration is scattered \u2014 a constant here, an environment variable there, a hardcoded value buried in a function. Django insists all of it lives in one predictable module: <code>settings.py</code>. It is read once, when the server starts, and held in memory for the life of the process.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>WHY IT EXISTS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p><code>settings.py</code> is just a plain Python module \u2014 there is no special syntax. It works because Django reads an environment variable called <code>DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE</code> at startup, imports that module, and then treats every UPPERCASE variable inside it as a configuration key. That's the entire trick: <strong>settings are just module-level variables Django agreed in advance to look for by name.</strong></p>\n<p>This matters philosophically: it means settings aren't a proprietary format you must memorize syntax for \u2014 they're regular Python, so you can use <code>if</code> statements, list comprehensions, or imports right inside the file to build settings dynamically (e.g. different settings for local vs. production).</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>The core settings, explained one by one</h3>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4><code>BASE_DIR</code></h4><span>PATH ANCHOR</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A <code>pathlib.Path</code> object pointing at your project's root folder. Every other path-based setting (templates, static files, the SQLite database file) is built relative to this, so the project still works no matter which machine or folder it's deployed into.</p>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> pathlib <span>import</span> Path\nBASE_DIR = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4><code>SECRET_KEY</code></h4><span>CRYPTOGRAPHIC SALT</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A long random string used to cryptographically sign things: session cookies, password-reset tokens, CSRF tokens. If someone obtains this key, they can forge valid-looking sessions and impersonate any user. <strong>It must never be committed to version control or hardcoded in shipped code.</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Critical Gotcha</h4><span>SECURITY</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>The default generated <code>SECRET_KEY</code> sits in plain text in <code>settings.py</code>. Beginners ship this straight to GitHub. The fix is to load it from an environment variable, with no hardcoded fallback in production:</p>\n<pre><code><span>import</span> os\nSECRET_KEY = os.environ[<span>\"DJANGO_SECRET_KEY\"</span>] <span># crashes loudly if missing \u2014 that's good</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4><code>DEBUG</code></h4><span>BOOLEAN SWITCH</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>When <code>True</code>, Django shows you detailed, gorgeous, dangerous error pages \u2014 full stack traces, your settings, your installed packages \u2014 directly in the browser. Essential while developing. <strong>Catastrophic in production</strong>, because anyone who triggers an error sees your internals, including secrets that leak into the traceback. The single most common security misconfiguration in beginner Django deployments is <code>DEBUG = True</code> left on in production.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4><code>ALLOWED_HOSTS</code></h4><span>LIST OF STRINGS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A guest list for your server. Django refuses to serve a response to any HTTP request whose <code>Host</code> header isn't on this list \u2014 this defends against a class of attack called HTTP Host header poisoning, where an attacker crafts a fake host header to trick your app into generating malicious password-reset links, etc.</p>\n<pre><code>ALLOWED_HOSTS = [<span>\"example.com\"</span>, <span>\"www.example.com\"</span>]</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4><code>INSTALLED_APPS</code></h4><span>LIST OF STRINGS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>This is the master switchboard. Every app \u2014 Django's built-in ones (<code>admin</code>, <code>auth</code>, <code>sessions</code>...) and every app you write yourself \u2014 must be listed here, or Django will not load its models, templates, admin registrations, or management commands. Forgetting to add an app here after <code>startapp</code> is one of the most common \"why isn't this working?!\" moments for newcomers.</p>\n<pre><code>INSTALLED_APPS = [\n <span>\"django.contrib.admin\"</span>,\n <span>\"django.contrib.auth\"</span>, <span># user accounts &amp; permissions</span>\n <span>\"django.contrib.contenttypes\"</span>, <span># generic relations between models</span>\n <span>\"django.contrib.sessions\"</span>, <span># server-side session storage</span>\n <span>\"django.contrib.messages\"</span>, <span># one-time flash messages</span>\n <span>\"django.contrib.staticfiles\"</span>, <span># CSS/JS/image serving helpers</span>\n <span>\"blog\"</span>, <span># &lt;-- your own app, added by hand</span>\n]</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4><code>MIDDLEWARE</code></h4><span>ORDERED LIST</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Middleware is a stack of small functions every request passes through <em>on the way in</em>, and every response passes through <em>on the way out</em> \u2014 in reverse order. It's the cleanest illustration of the philosophy \"common cross-cutting logic shouldn't live inside your view functions.\"</p>\n<figure class=\"diagram\">\n<svg aria-label=\"Diagram showing a request passing down through middleware layers to the view, then the response passing back up through the same layers in reverse\" role=\"img\" viewbox=\"0 0 600 170\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"300\" y=\"16\">MIDDLEWARE AS NESTED LAYERS</text>\n<rect fill=\"none\" height=\"35\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"560\" x=\"20\" y=\"30\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10.5\" x=\"30\" y=\"53\">SecurityMiddleware</text>\n<rect fill=\"none\" height=\"35\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"520\" x=\"40\" y=\"68\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10.5\" x=\"50\" y=\"91\">SessionMiddleware</text>\n<rect fill=\"#2f6b46\" height=\"35\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"480\" x=\"60\" y=\"106\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"300\" y=\"129\">YOUR VIEW</text>\n<path d=\"M40,18 L40,30\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8\" x=\"44\" y=\"20\">request \u2192</text>\n<text fill=\"#a3432e\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8\" x=\"500\" y=\"20\">\u2190 response</text>\n</svg>\n<figcaption>Request travels inward through each middleware; response travels back out in reverse order.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4><code>TEMPLATES</code> &amp; <code>DATABASES</code></h4><span>DICTIONARIES</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p><code>TEMPLATES</code> tells Django which templating engine to use and where to look for <code>.html</code> files. <code>DATABASES</code> defines connection info for your database \u2014 engine, name, host, credentials. Both default to sensible values (SQLite, Django's own template engine) so a fresh project works immediately with zero setup.</p>\n<pre><code>DATABASES = {\n <span>\"default\"</span>: {\n <span>\"ENGINE\"</span>: <span>\"django.db.backends.postgresql\"</span>,\n <span>\"NAME\"</span>: os.environ[<span>\"DB_NAME\"</span>],\n <span>\"USER\"</span>: os.environ[<span>\"DB_USER\"</span>],\n <span>\"PASSWORD\"</span>: os.environ[<span>\"DB_PASSWORD\"</span>],\n <span>\"HOST\"</span>: os.environ.get(<span>\"DB_HOST\"</span>, <span>\"localhost\"</span>),\n }\n}</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Pro Pattern</h4><span>SPLIT SETTINGS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Real production projects split <code>settings.py</code> into a package: <code>settings/base.py</code> (shared), <code>settings/dev.py</code>, <code>settings/prod.py</code>. Each environment-specific file starts with <code>from .base import *</code> and overrides only what differs. This avoids a single file riddled with <code>if DEBUG</code> branches and makes it obvious, at a glance, what changes between environments.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"urls\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 04 / ROUTING</span>\n<h2>urls.py \u2014 the dispatcher</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">In vanilla PHP-style development, the URL often <em>is</em> the file path \u2014 visiting <code>/about.php</code> directly executes <code>about.php</code>. Django decouples the two completely: URLs are an independent, declarative table that you control, mapping path patterns to Python functions.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>WHY DECOUPLE?</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A <code>urlpatterns</code> list is just that: a list. Each entry pairs a URL pattern with a view. When a request arrives, Django walks down the list, top to bottom, and uses the <strong>first pattern that matches</strong>. This means order matters, and it means your URLs can look like anything you want \u2014 clean, human-readable, SEO-friendly \u2014 completely independent of your folder structure or function names.</p>\n<p>This decoupling is powerful: you can rename a Python function without breaking a single bookmark, or change <code>/blog/post-1</code> to <code>/articles/post-1</code> without touching a line of view logic.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Project-level vs. app-level URLs</h3>\n<p>A small project can keep all routes in one file. A real one always splits them: the project's root <code>urls.py</code> delegates whole URL prefixes down into each app's own <code>urls.py</code> using <code>include()</code> \u2014 exactly like a switchboard operator forwarding your call to the right department's extension.</p>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">PROJECT ROOT \u2014 mysite/urls.py</span>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib <span>import</span> admin\n<span>from</span> django.urls <span>import</span> path, include\n\nurlpatterns = [\n path(<span>\"admin/\"</span>, admin.site.urls),\n path(<span>\"blog/\"</span>, include(<span>\"blog.urls\"</span>)),\n path(<span>\"accounts/\"</span>, include(<span>\"accounts.urls\"</span>)),\n]</code></pre>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">APP-LEVEL \u2014 blog/urls.py</span>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.urls <span>import</span> path\n<span>from</span> . <span>import</span> views\n\napp_name = <span>\"blog\"</span>\nurlpatterns = [\n path(<span>\"\"</span>, views.post_list, name=<span>\"list\"</span>),\n path(<span>\"&lt;int:pk&gt;/\"</span>, views.post_detail, name=<span>\"detail\"</span>),\n]</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Path converters \u2014 capturing pieces of the URL</h3>\n<p>The <code>&lt;int:pk&gt;</code> syntax above is a <strong>path converter</strong>. It captures a segment of the URL, validates its type, and passes it into your view function as an argument. This is Django doing input validation for you before your view code even runs.</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Converter</th><th>Matches</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>str</code></td><td>Any non-empty string without a slash (default)</td><td><code>&lt;str:username&gt;</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>int</code></td><td>Digits only, returns a Python <code>int</code></td><td><code>&lt;int:pk&gt;</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>slug</code></td><td>Letters, numbers, hyphens, underscores</td><td><code>&lt;slug:slug&gt;</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>uuid</code></td><td>A formatted UUID string</td><td><code>&lt;uuid:id&gt;</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>path</code></td><td>Any string, slashes included</td><td><code>&lt;path:filepath&gt;</code></td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Pro Pattern</h4><span>NAMED URLS \u2014 NEVER HARDCODE PATHS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Notice the <code>name=\"detail\"</code> argument. This lets you refer to a URL by a stable name instead of typing its raw string everywhere \u2014 so if the path ever changes, you fix it in <em>one</em> place.</p>\n<pre><code><span>&lt;!-- in a template --&gt;</span>\n&lt;a href=<span>\"{% url 'blog:detail' post.pk %}\"</span>&gt;Read more&lt;/a&gt;\n\n<span># in a view, redirecting after a form save</span>\n<span>from</span> django.urls <span>import</span> reverse\n<span>return</span> redirect(reverse(<span>\"blog:detail\"</span>, args=[post.pk]))</code></pre>\n<p>Hardcoding <code>\"/blog/3/\"</code> everywhere is the URL equivalent of hardcoding a magic number \u2014 it works until the structure changes, and then it breaks silently in fifteen places at once.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"views\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 05 / LOGIC</span>\n<h2>views.py \u2014 where decisions get made</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">A view is the closest thing to \"a regular function\" you write in Django, which is exactly why it feels familiar \u2014 and exactly why it's the most misunderstood piece for vanilla developers expecting it to be the HTML.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>THE CONTRACT</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Strip away everything else and a view is one rule: <strong>it takes an HTTP request, and it must return an HTTP response.</strong> That's the entire contract Django enforces. Everything else \u2014 querying the database, validating a form, choosing a template \u2014 is just stuff you do <em>in between</em> receiving the request and producing the response.</p>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.http <span>import</span> HttpResponse\n\n<span>def</span> <span>hello</span>(request):\n <span>return</span> HttpResponse(<span>\"Hello, world.\"</span>) <span># the absolute minimum valid view</span></code></pre>\n<p>Every \"feature\" you add on top \u2014 rendering a template, querying models, validating input \u2014 is sugar around that one rule. Once this clicks, Django views stop feeling magical.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Function-Based Views (FBVs) vs. Class-Based Views (CBVs)</h3>\n<p>Django gives you two ways to write the same contract. Neither is \"more correct\" \u2014 they're different tools for different shapes of problem.</p>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">FUNCTION-BASED VIEW</span>\n<p>A plain function. Reads top-to-bottom like a recipe. Best when the logic is simple, unique, or doesn't map cleanly to \"list this / show one of these / edit one of these.\"</p>\n<pre><code><span>def</span> <span>post_detail</span>(request, pk):\n post = get_object_or_404(Post, pk=pk)\n <span>return</span> render(\n request, <span>\"blog/detail.html\"</span>, {<span>\"post\"</span>: post}\n )</code></pre>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">CLASS-BASED VIEW</span>\n<p>A class inheriting from a generic view that already implements common patterns (list pages, detail pages, forms). You override only what differs. Best for the common 80% CRUD-shaped cases.</p>\n<pre><code><span>class</span> <span>PostDetail</span>(DetailView):\n model = Post\n template_name = <span>\"blog/detail.html\"</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Mental Model</h4><span>ANALOGY</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>FBVs are like writing a letter from scratch every time. CBVs are like filling in a mail-merge template \u2014 Django's generic views (<code>ListView</code>, <code>DetailView</code>, <code>CreateView</code>, <code>UpdateView</code>, <code>DeleteView</code>) already know the shape of \"show a list of things\" or \"show one thing and let it be edited.\" You only supply the blanks: which model, which template, which fields. The trade-off is the same as any template: faster for the common case, slightly more opaque when you need a deeply custom shape.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>The most important helper functions</h3>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Function</th><th>Does</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>render(request, template, context)</code></td><td>Loads a template, fills it with the <code>context</code> dictionary, returns an <code>HttpResponse</code>. The workhorse of nearly every view.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>redirect(to)</code></td><td>Returns an <code>HttpResponseRedirect</code> \u2014 tells the browser \"go fetch this other URL instead.\" Used after a successful form submission (the <strong>POST/redirect/GET pattern</strong>, which prevents double-submits on refresh).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>get_object_or_404(Model, **kwargs)</code></td><td>Fetches one row, or automatically raises a clean 404 page instead of a raw, ugly database exception. Replaces a manual <code>try/except</code> every single view would otherwise need.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>get_list_or_404(Model, **kwargs)</code></td><td>Same idea, for a queryset that must not be empty.</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>FAT VIEWS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Because a view <em>can</em> contain any Python, beginners often cram database logic, validation logic, and formatting logic all into one sprawling function. The healthier mental boundary: <strong>views orchestrate, models hold business rules, forms hold validation rules.</strong> A view should read like a short table of contents \u2014 \"validate this, fetch that, hand it to the template\" \u2014 not like the implementation of those steps.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"models\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 06 / DATA LAYER</span>\n<h2>models.py \u2014 what is a \"model,\" really, from absolute zero?</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">This is the concept most worth slowing down for, because it changes how you think about your database entirely. Let's build it from the ground up, with nothing assumed.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Absolute Scratch</h4><span>START HERE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>In vanilla development, you talk to a database by writing SQL strings: <code>SELECT * FROM posts WHERE id = 1</code>. You get back rows of raw data \u2014 tuples, dicts \u2014 that have no behavior, no validation, no relationships beyond what your SQL joins manually reconstruct.</p>\n<p>A <strong>model</strong> is Django's answer to one question: <em>what if a database table could be represented as a normal Python class, and a row in that table could be a normal Python object?</em></p>\n<p>That's it. That's the whole idea. A model class describes the <strong>shape</strong> of your data \u2014 what fields exist, what type each field is, what rules each field follows (required? unique? a maximum length?) \u2014 and Django uses that one description for three completely different jobs simultaneously:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>It generates the actual SQL</strong> needed to create the table (via migrations).</li>\n<li><strong>It gives you a Python API</strong> to create, read, update, and delete rows without writing SQL by hand (the ORM \u2014 \"Object-Relational Mapper\").</li>\n<li><strong>It powers the admin panel and forms automatically</strong>, because they can introspect the model and build UI for it.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This is the deepest \"aha\" in Django: <strong>you describe your data once, and that single description radiates outward into your database schema, your Python objects, your admin UI, and your forms.</strong> Change the model, and all four of those things can update in lockstep.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Building one, piece by piece</h3>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.db <span>import</span> models\n\n<span>class</span> <span>Post</span>(models.Model):\n title = models.CharField(max_length=200)\n slug = models.SlugField(unique=True)\n body = models.TextField()\n published = models.BooleanField(default=False)\n created_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)\n author = models.ForeignKey(\n <span>\"auth.User\"</span>, on_delete=models.CASCADE, related_name=<span>\"posts\"</span>\n )\n\n <span>def</span> <span>__str__</span>(self):\n <span>return</span> self.title</code></pre>\n<p>Read this line by line, the way a vanilla developer should read it the first time:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>class Post(models.Model)</code> \u2014 declares a new database table. Inheriting from <code>models.Model</code> is what flips on all the ORM behavior; without it, this is just a regular class.</li>\n<li>Each line like <code>title = models.CharField(...)</code> becomes <strong>one column</strong> in the table. The class attribute name (<code>title</code>) becomes the column name and the Python attribute name, simultaneously.</li>\n<li><code>CharField</code>, <code>TextField</code>, <code>BooleanField</code>, <code>DateTimeField</code> are <strong>field types</strong> \u2014 they map to specific SQL column types (<code>VARCHAR</code>, <code>TEXT</code>, <code>BOOLEAN</code>, <code>TIMESTAMP</code>) and also enforce Python-level validation (e.g. <code>CharField</code> requires <code>max_length</code>).</li>\n<li><code>ForeignKey</code> is a <strong>relationship</strong>, not a plain field \u2014 it links every <code>Post</code> to exactly one <code>User</code>, and <code>on_delete=models.CASCADE</code> answers the question \"what happens to this post if its author's account is deleted?\" (here: delete the post too).</li>\n<li><code>__str__</code> isn't required, but defines the human-readable label Django shows for this object everywhere \u2014 admin lists, debug shells, error pages. Skipping it means seeing unhelpful labels like <code>Post object (1)</code> everywhere.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Field types \u2014 a working reference</h3>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Stores</th><th>Common arguments</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>CharField</code></td><td>Short text</td><td><code>max_length</code> (required)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>TextField</code></td><td>Long, unbounded text</td><td>\u2014</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>IntegerField</code></td><td>Whole numbers</td><td><code>default</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>DecimalField</code></td><td>Exact decimals (money!)</td><td><code>max_digits</code>, <code>decimal_places</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>BooleanField</code></td><td>True / False</td><td><code>default</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>DateTimeField</code></td><td>Date + time</td><td><code>auto_now_add</code> (set once, on creation), <code>auto_now</code> (updated on every save)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>EmailField</code></td><td>Text, validated as email shape</td><td><code>max_length</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SlugField</code></td><td>URL-safe short text (<code>my-post-title</code>)</td><td><code>unique</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>ForeignKey</code></td><td>Many-to-one relationship</td><td><code>on_delete</code> (required), <code>related_name</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>ManyToManyField</code></td><td>Many-to-many relationship</td><td><code>related_name</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>OneToOneField</code></td><td>Strict one-to-one link</td><td><code>on_delete</code></td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span><code>on_delete</code> IS NOT OPTIONAL</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Every <code>ForeignKey</code> and <code>OneToOneField</code> requires an <code>on_delete</code> argument, because Django forces you to make an explicit decision about referential integrity rather than letting it default silently. The common options:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>models.CASCADE</code> \u2014 delete this row too, if the parent is deleted (comments die with their post).</li>\n<li><code>models.PROTECT</code> \u2014 refuse to delete the parent at all while this row exists.</li>\n<li><code>models.SET_NULL</code> \u2014 set this field to <code>NULL</code> instead (requires the field to allow <code>null=True</code>).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>The ORM in action \u2014 Python instead of SQL</h3>\n<p>Once a model exists, here is the same handful of SQL operations, side by side with their ORM equivalent \u2014 this comparison is the fastest way to internalize the mapping:</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Raw SQL</th><th>Django ORM</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>INSERT INTO post (title, body) VALUES (...)</code></td><td><code>Post.objects.create(title=\"Hi\", body=\"...\")</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SELECT * FROM post</code></td><td><code>Post.objects.all()</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SELECT * FROM post WHERE published = true</code></td><td><code>Post.objects.filter(published=True)</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SELECT * FROM post WHERE id = 1</code></td><td><code>Post.objects.get(pk=1)</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>UPDATE post SET title='New' WHERE id=1</code></td><td><code>post.title = \"New\"; post.save()</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>DELETE FROM post WHERE id=1</code></td><td><code>post.delete()</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SELECT * FROM post ORDER BY created_at DESC</code></td><td><code>Post.objects.order_by(\"-created_at\")</code></td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><code>Post.objects</code> is called the <strong>manager</strong> \u2014 every model gets one automatically. It's the gateway to every database query for that model. <code>QuerySet</code>s (the thing <code>.filter()</code> and <code>.all()</code> return) are <strong>lazy</strong>: building one doesn't hit the database at all. The actual SQL only fires the moment you iterate over it, print it, or call something like <code>len()</code> on it.</p>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>LAZINESS IS A FEATURE, NOT A BUG</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Because querysets are lazy, you can chain filters and Django will combine them into <em>one</em> efficient SQL query at the moment it actually runs \u2014 instead of running three separate queries:</p>\n<pre><code>posts = Post.objects.filter(published=True).order_by(<span>\"-created_at\"</span>)[:5]\n<span># no SQL has executed yet \u2014 this is just a description of intent</span>\n<span>for</span> post <span>in</span> posts: <span># NOW it runs, once, fully optimized</span>\n print(post.title)</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>THE N+1 QUERY PROBLEM</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>The single most common Django performance bug. Looping over posts and accessing <code>post.author.name</code> inside the loop fires a brand-new query <em>per post</em> to fetch each author \u2014 N posts means N+1 total queries. The fix is to tell Django to fetch related rows upfront:</p>\n<pre><code>Post.objects.select_related(<span>\"author\"</span>) <span># for ForeignKey / OneToOne \u2014 one JOIN</span>\nPost.objects.prefetch_related(<span>\"tags\"</span>) <span># for ManyToMany / reverse FK \u2014 one extra query</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Mental Model</h4><span>THE FULL PICTURE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>If a <strong>vanilla SQL table</strong> is a spreadsheet, and a <strong>raw query result</strong> is a printed copy of one row of that spreadsheet with no context \u2014 a <strong>Django model instance</strong> is a living object that remembers which spreadsheet it came from, knows how to update itself, and can walk its own relationships ( <code>post.author.email</code>, <code>post.comments.all()</code> ) the same way any nested Python object can. The model class is the spreadsheet's column headers and rules; an instance is one filled-in row, brought to life as an object.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"migrations\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 07 / SCHEMA HISTORY</span>\n<h2>Migrations \u2014 version control for your database</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">In vanilla projects, the database schema is often a one-off SQL script you run manually and then forget about, with no record of how it evolved. Django treats schema changes the same way you treat code changes \u2014 as a sequence of committed, reviewable, reversible files.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>TWO COMMANDS, TWO JOBS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>There are exactly two steps, and conflating them is the most common beginner mistake:</p>\n<pre><code><span>python</span> manage.py makemigrations <span># STEP 1 \u2014 write the plan</span>\n<span>python</span> manage.py migrate <span># STEP 2 \u2014 execute the plan</span></code></pre>\n<p><code>makemigrations</code> compares your current <code>models.py</code> against the last known schema state and writes a new Python file describing the difference \u2014 \"add column X,\" \"remove field Y.\" It does <strong>not</strong> touch the database at all. It only writes a plan to disk.</p>\n<p><code>migrate</code> reads all migration files that haven't been applied yet, and actually runs the SQL against your real database, in order.</p>\n<p>This two-step separation exists so the generated plan can be reviewed, edited, and committed to git <em>before</em> it ever touches real data \u2014 exactly the same caution you'd want before running any destructive operation.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<figure class=\"diagram\">\n<svg aria-label=\"Diagram showing the migration lifecycle: edit models.py, run makemigrations to generate a migration file, then run migrate to apply it to the database\" role=\"img\" viewbox=\"0 0 640 140\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"60\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"150\" x=\"10\" y=\"40\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"85\" y=\"65\">models.py</text>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"85\" y=\"82\">you edit this</text>\n<rect fill=\"#2f6b46\" height=\"60\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"150\" x=\"245\" y=\"40\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"320\" y=\"60\">0007_add_slug.py</text>\n<text fill=\"#D9E7DD\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"320\" y=\"78\">generated plan</text>\n<text fill=\"#D9E7DD\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"320\" y=\"91\">(makemigrations)</text>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"60\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"150\" x=\"480\" y=\"40\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"555\" y=\"65\">DATABASE</text>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"555\" y=\"82\">(migrate)</text>\n<path d=\"M160,70 L243,70\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\"></path>\n<path d=\"M395,70 L478,70\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\"></path>\n</svg>\n<figcaption>Model change \u2192 generated plan file \u2192 applied schema change. Two distinct, inspectable steps.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>NEVER EDIT THE DATABASE BY HAND</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>If you manually alter a table outside of Django's migration system (say, in a database GUI), Django's internal migration history no longer matches reality. Future migrations will assume a schema state that doesn't exist, and you'll get baffling errors. The rule: <strong>once a project is on migrations, all schema changes go through migrations \u2014 no exceptions.</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>COMMIT MIGRATION FILES TO GIT</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Migration files are code, not build artifacts \u2014 never <code>.gitignore</code> them. Every developer on a team, and every deployment environment, needs the exact same sequence of migrations to construct an identical schema.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"admin\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 08 / BACK OFFICE</span>\n<h2>admin.py \u2014 the free back office</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">In vanilla development, building a CRUD dashboard so non-technical staff can manage content is an entire project on its own \u2014 forms, validation, permission checks, list pages, search. Django ships this entire app for free, and <code>admin.py</code> is simply the file where you tell it which of your models deserve a presence in that dashboard.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>WHY IT'S FREE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Remember Sheet 06: a model already fully describes its own fields and types. The admin app reads that same description and auto-generates list views, detail/edit forms, search, filtering, and pagination \u2014 all without you writing a line of HTML. You're not building an admin panel; you're <strong>registering</strong> your models with one that already exists.</p>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib <span>import</span> admin\n<span>from</span> .models <span>import</span> Post\n\nadmin.site.register(Post) <span># the absolute minimum \u2014 Post now has a full CRUD UI</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Customizing the admin \u2014 ModelAdmin</h3>\n<p>The bare <code>register()</code> call works, but real projects almost always customize the experience with a <code>ModelAdmin</code> subclass, which controls how the list page and edit form look and behave.</p>\n<pre><code><span>@admin.register</span>(Post)\n<span>class</span> <span>PostAdmin</span>(admin.ModelAdmin):\n list_display = (<span>\"title\"</span>, <span>\"author\"</span>, <span>\"published\"</span>, <span>\"created_at\"</span>)\n list_filter = (<span>\"published\"</span>, <span>\"author\"</span>)\n search_fields = (<span>\"title\"</span>, <span>\"body\"</span>)\n prepopulated_fields = {<span>\"slug\"</span>: (<span>\"title\"</span>,)} <span># auto-fills slug as you type the title</span></code></pre>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Attribute</th><th>Controls</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>list_display</code></td><td>Which columns show on the list page</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>list_filter</code></td><td>Sidebar filters on the list page</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>search_fields</code></td><td>Which fields the search box queries</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>readonly_fields</code></td><td>Fields shown but not editable</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>list_editable</code></td><td>Fields editable directly from the list page, no detail click needed</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>THE ADMIN IS NOT YOUR PUBLIC SITE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>It's tempting to treat <code>/admin/</code> as a shortcut to skip building real frontend pages. Resist this for anything end users touch \u2014 the admin is a tool for trusted staff, not a substitute for your application's actual views, forms, and templates. It also has no built-in rate limiting against brute-force login attempts at the URL path itself, so production projects commonly move it off the default <code>/admin/</code> path and add extra protections (2FA, IP allowlisting) for genuinely sensitive deployments.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"forms\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 09 / INPUT &amp; TRUST</span>\n<h2>forms.py \u2014 never trust the network</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">In vanilla code, handling a submitted form means manually reading <code>request.POST</code>, manually checking each field is present, manually checking its type and length, manually re-rendering the form with error messages if something's wrong, and manually guarding against cross-site request forgery. Django's forms system exists to centralize every one of those repetitive, security-critical steps.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>THE GOLDEN RULE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>The foundational rule of all web security: <strong>never trust data that arrives from a client.</strong> Anyone can send any bytes to any URL your server exposes, regardless of what your own HTML form looks like \u2014 a malicious actor doesn't need your form at all, just your URL. A Django <code>Form</code> (or <code>ModelForm</code>) is a single declared object that knows the rules incoming data must satisfy, validates it the moment it's received, and refuses to let unsafe or malformed data anywhere near your database.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Form vs. ModelForm</h3>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\"><code>forms.Form</code></span>\n<p>A plain form unconnected to any model \u2014 a contact form, a search box, a login form. You declare every field by hand.</p>\n<pre><code><span>class</span> <span>ContactForm</span>(forms.Form):\n name = forms.CharField(max_length=100)\n email = forms.EmailField()\n message = forms.CharField(widget=forms.Textarea)</code></pre>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\"><code>forms.ModelForm</code></span>\n<p>A form generated <em>from</em> a model \u2014 fields, types, and validation are inherited automatically. The natural choice for \"create/edit this database row\" screens.</p>\n<pre><code><span>class</span> <span>PostForm</span>(forms.ModelForm):\n <span>class</span> <span>Meta</span>:\n model = Post\n fields = [<span>\"title\"</span>, <span>\"slug\"</span>, <span>\"body\"</span>]</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>The full lifecycle, inside a view</h3>\n<pre><code><span>def</span> <span>create_post</span>(request):\n <span>if</span> request.method == <span>\"POST\"</span>:\n form = PostForm(request.POST)\n <span>if</span> form.is_valid(): <span># runs every field's validation rules</span>\n post = form.save() <span># writes a real row to the database</span>\n <span>return</span> redirect(<span>\"blog:detail\"</span>, pk=post.pk)\n <span>else</span>:\n form = PostForm() <span># empty, unbound form for the initial GET</span>\n <span>return</span> render(request, <span>\"blog/form.html\"</span>, {<span>\"form\"</span>: form})</code></pre>\n<p>This pattern \u2014 <strong>check the method, validate, save-or-redisplay-with-errors</strong> \u2014 is so universal across Django projects it's worth memorizing as a single mental shape, the way a vanilla developer memorizes a basic <code>for</code> loop.</p>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>CSRF TOKEN</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Every POST form in a template needs <code>{% csrf_token %}</code> inside the <code>&lt;form&gt;</code> tag, or Django's <code>CsrfViewMiddleware</code> rejects the submission with a 403. This isn't bureaucracy \u2014 it's the defense against Cross-Site Request Forgery, where a malicious site tries to silently submit a form to your site using a logged-in user's own browser session.</p>\n<pre><code>&lt;form method=<span>\"post\"</span>&gt;\n {% csrf_token %}\n {{ form }}\n &lt;button type=<span>\"submit\"</span>&gt;Save&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;/form&gt;</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>VALIDATION LIVES IN TWO PLACES, ON PURPOSE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Field-level constraints (<code>max_length</code>, required) belong on the field itself. Cross-field business rules (\"end date must be after start date\") belong in a <code>clean()</code> method on the form, which runs after individual fields pass:</p>\n<pre><code><span>def</span> <span>clean</span>(self):\n cleaned = super().clean()\n <span>if</span> cleaned.get(<span>\"end\"</span>) and cleaned[<span>\"end\"</span>] &lt; cleaned.get(<span>\"start\"</span>):\n <span>raise</span> forms.ValidationError(<span>\"End date must be after start date.\"</span>)</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"templates\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 10 / PRESENTATION</span>\n<h2>Templates \u2014 HTML with a brain, on a leash</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Templates are where Django's MVT name finally clicks: this is the \"face\" \u2014 the actual markup. The Django Template Language (DTL) intentionally avoids letting you write arbitrary Python inside HTML, and that restriction is itself a design philosophy.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>WHY A RESTRICTED LANGUAGE?</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>If templates could run any Python, designers and developers could no longer safely divide labor \u2014 a typo in a template could crash the whole page in unpredictable ways, and business logic would leak into HTML files. The DTL deliberately offers a small vocabulary: variable output, simple loops, simple conditionals, and \"filters\" for light formatting. Anything more complex is supposed to happen in the view or the model \u2014 templates render, they don't decide.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Syntax</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>{{ variable }}</code></td><td>Print a value from the context</td><td><code>{{ post.title }}</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>{% tag %}</code></td><td>Logic \u2014 loops, conditionals, includes</td><td><code>{% for p in posts %}...{% endfor %}</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>{{ var\\|filter }}</code></td><td>Transform a value before printing</td><td><code>{{ post.body\\|truncatewords:30 }}</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>{% extends %}</code></td><td>Inherit a parent layout</td><td><code>{% extends \"base.html\" %}</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>{% block %}</code></td><td>Define a fillable region in a layout</td><td><code>{% block content %}{% endblock %}</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>{% include %}</code></td><td>Insert another template file inline</td><td><code>{% include \"nav.html\" %}</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>{% url %}</code></td><td>Build a link from a named URL</td><td><code>{% url 'blog:detail' post.pk %}</code></td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3>Template inheritance \u2014 the DRY principle, visually</h3>\n<p>Nearly every real site shares a header, nav, and footer across pages. Rewriting that HTML in every file is the templating equivalent of copy-pasting a function body. Inheritance solves it the same way subclassing solves it in Python: define the shared skeleton once, and let child templates plug content into named holes.</p>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">base.html \u2014 the skeleton</span>\n<pre><code>&lt;html&gt;\n &lt;body&gt;\n {% include <span>\"nav.html\"</span> %}\n {% block content %}{% endblock %}\n {% include <span>\"footer.html\"</span> %}\n &lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">detail.html \u2014 fills the hole</span>\n<pre><code>{% extends <span>\"base.html\"</span> %}\n{% block content %}\n &lt;h1&gt;{{ post.title }}&lt;/h1&gt;\n &lt;p&gt;{{ post.body }}&lt;/p&gt;\n{% endblock %}</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>AUTO-ESCAPING IS ON BY DEFAULT \u2014 AND THAT'S CORRECT</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Every variable Django prints through <code>{{ }}</code> is automatically HTML-escaped \u2014 <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> becomes harmless text rather than executing. This is the framework's default defense against Cross-Site Scripting (XSS). Only disable it (<code>{{ value|safe }}</code> or <code>{% autoescape off %}</code>) for content you are absolutely certain is trustworthy \u2014 never for raw user input.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"tests\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 11 / VERIFICATION</span>\n<h2>tests.py \u2014 proving the blueprint holds weight</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">In vanilla projects, \"testing\" often means manually clicking through the site after each change and hoping nothing broke. Django builds on Python's standard <code>unittest</code> framework and adds a test client that can simulate full HTTP requests without ever starting a real server or touching your real database.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>WHAT MAKES A DJANGO TEST SPECIAL</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A <code>django.test.TestCase</code> wraps every test method in a database transaction that's automatically rolled back the instant the test ends \u2014 so tests can freely create, modify, and delete data without ever touching your real development database, and without tests interfering with each other's data. This is what makes it safe to write tests that hit the database constantly.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.test <span>import</span> TestCase\n<span>from</span> django.urls <span>import</span> reverse\n<span>from</span> .models <span>import</span> Post\n\n<span>class</span> <span>PostModelTests</span>(TestCase):\n <span>def</span> <span>test_str_returns_title</span>(self):\n post = Post.objects.create(title=<span>\"Hello\"</span>, body=<span>\"...\"</span>)\n self.assertEqual(str(post), <span>\"Hello\"</span>)\n\n<span>class</span> <span>PostViewTests</span>(TestCase):\n <span>def</span> <span>test_detail_page_returns_200</span>(self):\n post = Post.objects.create(title=<span>\"Hello\"</span>, body=<span>\"...\"</span>)\n response = self.client.get(reverse(<span>\"blog:detail\"</span>, args=[post.pk]))\n self.assertEqual(response.status_code, 200)\n self.assertContains(response, <span>\"Hello\"</span>)</code></pre>\n<p><code>self.client</code> is the test client \u2014 it can <code>.get()</code> and <code>.post()</code> any URL exactly like a browser would, then lets you assert against the resulting status code, content, redirects, or template used.</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Test type</th><th>Verifies</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Model tests</td><td>Field defaults, custom methods, <code>__str__</code>, validation logic, model-level business rules.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>View tests</td><td>Correct status codes, correct template used, correct context data, permission/redirect behavior for logged-out users.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Form tests</td><td>Valid data passes, invalid data is rejected with the right error, <code>clean()</code> cross-field rules work.</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>RUNNING TESTS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<pre><code><span>python</span> manage.py <span>test</span> <span># run everything</span>\n<span>python</span> manage.py <span>test</span> blog <span># just one app</span>\n<span>python</span> manage.py <span>test</span> blog.tests.PostViewTests <span># one class</span></code></pre>\n<p>A practical rule for newcomers: write a test the moment you fix a bug. It documents the bug existed, and guarantees it can never silently come back.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"wsgi-asgi\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 12 / SERVER ENTRY POINTS</span>\n<h2>wsgi.py &amp; asgi.py \u2014 the doorways into Django</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">These two tiny files are the part of Django most vanilla developers never even open, yet they answer a fundamental question: how does an actual web server (Gunicorn, uWSGI, Daphne, Uvicorn) hand a request <em>into</em> your Python code in the first place?</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>THE PROBLEM THEY SOLVE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A real production web server is written to handle raw TCP connections, HTTP parsing, concurrency, and process management efficiently \u2014 that's a different job than business logic. So the industry standardized a contract: a web server can talk to <em>any</em> Python web application, of any framework, as long as that application exposes one standard callable function with an agreed-upon signature. That standard is <strong>WSGI</strong> (Web Server Gateway Interface) for synchronous apps, and its newer sibling <strong>ASGI</strong> (Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface) for apps that need async support (WebSockets, long-lived connections, <code>async def</code> views).</p>\n<p><code>wsgi.py</code> and <code>asgi.py</code> each expose exactly one thing: an <code>application</code> object that is Django's side of that handshake. The production server calls into <code>application</code>; Django takes it from there \u2014 middleware, URL resolution, your view, and back out.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<pre><code><span># wsgi.py \u2014 generated automatically, rarely needs edits</span>\n<span>import</span> os\n<span>from</span> django.core.wsgi <span>import</span> get_wsgi_application\n\nos.environ.setdefault(<span>\"DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE\"</span>, <span>\"mysite.settings\"</span>)\napplication = get_wsgi_application()</code></pre>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th></th><th>WSGI</th><th>ASGI</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Model</td><td>Synchronous, one request per worker thread/process at a time</td><td>Asynchronous, can juggle many connections concurrently on one worker</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Good for</td><td>Standard request/response pages \u2014 the vast majority of sites</td><td>WebSockets, Server-Sent Events, long-polling, high-concurrency I/O-bound work</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Common servers</td><td>Gunicorn, uWSGI</td><td>Daphne, Uvicorn</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>manage.py runserver</code></td><td colspan=\"2\">Django's own dev server speaks both \u2014 fine for local development, <strong>never</strong> for production traffic.</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Mental Model</h4><span>ANALOGY</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Think of WSGI/ASGI as a universal electrical socket standard. The web server is the wall socket \u2014 it doesn't care what brand of appliance you plug in. <code>wsgi.py</code>/<code>asgi.py</code> are the plug adapter on your appliance (Django), shaped exactly to that standard, so any compliant socket can power it without custom wiring.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"odds\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 13 / EVERYTHING ELSE</span>\n<h2>manage.py, apps.py, and the rest of the toolbox</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Beyond the core MVT trio, a handful of supporting files round out the picture \u2014 small individually, but each solving a specific recurring problem.</p>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>manage.py</h4><span>COMMAND-LINE REMOTE CONTROL</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A thin script that sets <code>DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE</code> and forwards everything else to Django's command system. Every command you run \u2014 <code>runserver</code>, <code>migrate</code>, <code>test</code>, <code>shell</code>, <code>createsuperuser</code> \u2014 passes through here. It exists so you never have to remember which settings module to point at by hand.</p>\n<pre><code><span>python</span> manage.py runserver <span># start the dev server</span>\n<span>python</span> manage.py shell <span># a Python REPL with your models pre-importable</span>\n<span>python</span> manage.py createsuperuser <span># make an admin account interactively</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>apps.py</h4><span>APP-LEVEL CONFIG</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A small <code>AppConfig</code> subclass each app gets automatically. Mostly invisible until you need its one common real use: registering <strong>signals</strong> (see below) reliably at startup, via a <code>ready()</code> method.</p>\n<pre><code><span>class</span> <span>BlogConfig</span>(AppConfig):\n default_auto_field = <span>\"django.db.models.BigAutoField\"</span>\n name = <span>\"blog\"</span>\n\n <span>def</span> <span>ready</span>(self):\n <span>import</span> blog.signals <span># noqa</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Signals</h4><span>DECOUPLED REACTIONS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A publish/subscribe mechanism: certain events (a model is about to save, has just saved, is about to delete) broadcast a signal that any other piece of code can listen for \u2014 without the model itself needing to know who's listening. Useful, but easy to overuse into invisible, hard-to-trace side effects; reach for an explicit method call first, and a signal only when the listener genuinely belongs in a different app.</p>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.db.models.signals <span>import</span> post_save\n<span>from</span> django.dispatch <span>import</span> receiver\n\n<span>@receiver</span>(post_save, sender=Post)\n<span>def</span> <span>notify_subscribers</span>(sender, instance, created, **kwargs):\n <span>if</span> created:\n send_new_post_email(instance)</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Static files vs. media files</h4><span>A DISTINCTION WORTH KEEPING STRAIGHT</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p><strong>Static files</strong> are assets that ship <em>with your code</em> \u2014 CSS, JavaScript, your own logo. They're collected once at deploy time via <code>collectstatic</code> into <code>STATIC_ROOT</code>. <strong>Media files</strong> are content <em>uploaded by users at runtime</em> \u2014 profile pictures, attachments \u2014 stored under <code>MEDIA_ROOT</code>. Conflating the two is a common misconfiguration: static files belong in source control or a build pipeline; media files almost never do.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Management commands</h4><span>CUSTOM CLI TOOLS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Any app can define its own <code>manage.py</code> subcommand by adding a file to <code>app/management/commands/</code>. Useful for one-off data imports, scheduled maintenance tasks, or anything you'd otherwise write as a disconnected standalone script.</p>\n<pre><code><span># blog/management/commands/purge_drafts.py</span>\n<span>from</span> django.core.management.base <span>import</span> BaseCommand\n\n<span>class</span> <span>Command</span>(BaseCommand):\n <span>def</span> <span>handle</span>(self, *args, **options):\n Post.objects.filter(published=False).delete()\n self.stdout.write(<span>\"Drafts purged.\"</span>)</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"flow\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 14 / SYNTHESIS</span>\n<h2>Tracing one request, start to finish</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Everything above is a separate file. Here is how they cooperate, traced through a single concrete example: a browser visiting <code>/blog/3/</code>.</p>\n<figure class=\"diagram\">\n<svg aria-label=\"Step by step diagram tracing a request through WSGI, middleware, urls.py, views.py, models.py, the database, the template, and back to the browser\" role=\"img\" viewbox=\"0 0 700 560\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10\" letter-spacing=\"1.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"350\" y=\"20\">GET /blog/3/ \u2014 STEP BY STEP</text>\n<g font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\">\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"38\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"64\">1 \u00b7 Browser sends HTTP request</text>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-size=\"9.5\" x=\"430\" y=\"64\">GET /blog/3/ HTTP/1.1</text>\n<path d=\"M350,82 L350,98\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"98\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"124\">2 \u00b7 wsgi.py / asgi.py receives it</text>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-size=\"9.5\" x=\"430\" y=\"124\">server \u2192 application()</text>\n<path d=\"M350,142 L350,158\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"158\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"184\">3 \u00b7 Middleware stack runs (inbound)</text>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-size=\"9.5\" x=\"430\" y=\"184\">security, session, auth...</text>\n<path d=\"M350,202 L350,218\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#2f6b46\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"218\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"244\">4 \u00b7 urls.py matches the pattern</text>\n<text fill=\"#D9E7DD\" font-size=\"9.5\" x=\"430\" y=\"244\">&lt;int:pk&gt; captures pk=3</text>\n<path d=\"M350,262 L350,278\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#2f6b46\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"278\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"304\">5 \u00b7 views.post_detail(request, pk=3) runs</text>\n<path d=\"M350,322 L350,338\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"338\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"364\">6 \u00b7 models.Post asks the database</text>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-size=\"9.5\" x=\"430\" y=\"364\">get_object_or_404(Post, pk=3)</text>\n<path d=\"M350,382 L350,398\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"398\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"424\">7 \u00b7 render() loads the template + context</text>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-size=\"9.5\" x=\"430\" y=\"424\">blog/detail.html</text>\n<path d=\"M350,442 L350,458\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"458\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"484\">8 \u00b7 Middleware stack runs (outbound, reversed)</text>\n<path d=\"M350,502 L350,518\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#1c1a16\" height=\"40\" stroke=\"#c8a15c\" stroke-width=\"1.6\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"518\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"350\" y=\"543\">9 \u00b7 Finished HTML returns to the browser as an HttpResponse</text>\n</g>\n</svg>\n<figcaption>Nine steps, nine files, one request. Every sheet in this guide is one stop on this line.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<div class=\"pillquote\">\"Once you can narrate this diagram from memory, you no longer need this guide \u2014 you understand Django.\"</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"tips\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 15 / FIELD NOTES</span>\n<h2>Pro tips, conventions, and traps to avoid</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">A consolidated punch list \u2014 the kind of thing a senior teammate tells you in your first week so you don't learn it the hard way.</p>\n<h3>Project hygiene</h3>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Keep one virtual environment per project (<code>python -m venv venv</code>) \u2014 never install packages globally.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Pin dependencies with a <code>requirements.txt</code> (or Poetry/uv lockfile) so deploys are reproducible.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Never commit <code>.env</code>, <code>SECRET_KEY</code>, or database credentials \u2014 use <code>django-environ</code> or plain <code>os.environ</code>.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Run <code>DEBUG = False</code> and a real <code>ALLOWED_HOSTS</code> before anything touches the public internet.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Code organization</h3>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n<li class=\"tone-success\">\"Fat models, thin views\" \u2014 push business logic into model methods or a service layer, keep views orchestration-only.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Use <code>related_name</code> on every <code>ForeignKey</code> so reverse lookups read naturally (<code>author.posts.all()</code> instead of Django's default, uglier auto-name).</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Prefer <code>get_object_or_404</code> over manual <code>try/except DoesNotExist</code> in views \u2014 it's shorter and gives users a proper 404 page.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Name URLs and reference them with <code>{% url %}</code> / <code>reverse()</code> \u2014 never hardcode path strings.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Performance</h3>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Watch for N+1 queries; reach for <code>select_related</code> / <code>prefetch_related</code> the moment you loop and touch a relation.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Use Django's <code>django-debug-toolbar</code> locally \u2014 it shows you the exact SQL each page ran, instantly surfacing N+1 problems.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Cache expensive, rarely-changing pages or querysets with Django's cache framework rather than re-computing them every request.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Security checklist before going live</h3>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">MUST DO</span>\n<ul>\n<li><code>DEBUG = False</code></li>\n<li>Real, narrow <code>ALLOWED_HOSTS</code></li>\n<li><code>SECRET_KEY</code> from environment, never in git</li>\n<li>HTTPS enforced (<code>SECURE_SSL_REDIRECT</code>)</li>\n<li><code>CSRF_COOKIE_SECURE</code> / <code>SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE</code> on</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">RUN BEFORE DEPLOY</span>\n<pre><code><span>python</span> manage.py check --deploy</code></pre>\n<p>Django's built-in production readiness auditor \u2014 it inspects your live settings and flags exactly these gaps with specific fixes.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>THE SHELL IS YOUR BEST DEBUGGING FRIEND</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p><code>python manage.py shell</code> drops you into a Python REPL with Django fully configured \u2014 import any model and query it live, exactly as your views would, to sanity-check assumptions before writing a single line of view code.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"uiux\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 16 / DESIGN NOTES</span>\n<h2>The UI/UX decisions behind this document, made explicit</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Since this guide is itself a piece of interface design, here is the reasoning behind it \u2014 the same kind of intentionality worth bringing to any Django admin, dashboard, or end-user screen you build.</p>\n<div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">CONSISTENT VISUAL VOCABULARY</span>\n<p>Every concept uses the same three box types \u2014 concept, tip, warning \u2014 so within two sheets, a reader recognizes a box's purpose by its border color and corner mark alone, before reading a word.</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">PROGRESSIVE DISCLOSURE</span>\n<p>Each sheet follows the same rhythm: plain-language concept first, code second, gotchas and pro tips last \u2014 matching how understanding actually builds, from \"why\" to \"how\" to \"watch out.\"</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">SCANABILITY OVER DENSITY</span>\n<p>Sticky nav, a sheet index, generous line-length limits (~74 characters), and a strict heading hierarchy mean a reader can jump straight to <code>forms.py</code> without reading the rest top-to-bottom.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Why a \"blueprint\" metaphor specifically</h3>\n<p>Django itself describes its job as giving you the structural skeleton of a site while you fill in the unique parts \u2014 a blueprint, not a finished building. The visual system leans into that literally: grid-paper background, corner registration marks (the kind printers use to align multi-pass prints), and a recurring title block (the stamp box every architectural drawing carries in its corner) all reinforce, on every single screen, that you are looking at <em>structure</em> \u2014 which is exactly what Django is.</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Principle</th><th>Applied here as</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Accessibility</td><td>Visible focus outlines, semantic headings, <code>aria-label</code> on every diagram, color contrast checked against the cream background, reduced-motion respected.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Typographic hierarchy</td><td>A characterful serif (Fraunces) for display headings only, a clean sans (Inter) for body copy, and a monospace (JetBrains Mono) reserved exclusively for code, labels, and technical metadata \u2014 three distinct jobs, three distinct faces.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Responsive layout</td><td>Two-column grids collapse to one column under 760\u2013900px; the hero diagram and nav remain legible at phone widths.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Signature element</td><td>The title block and corner registration marks recur on every sheet \u2014 the one consistent visual signature tying sixteen very different topics into one document.</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"pillquote\">\"Good documentation design and good Django architecture solve the same problem: making a large, unfamiliar structure feel predictable at a glance.\"</div>\n</div>\n</section>";

